    <title>Combined summary - Weak block thoughts...</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T22:56:28.006834+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-September/011159.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The concept of weak blocks was introduced to the Bitcoin community in 2015 as a way to improve block propagation speed across the network. Weak blocks are pre-announced by miners before solving the proof-of-work puzzle and are quickly validated by peers to improve block propagation speed. When a full-difficulty block is found based on a previously announced weak block, block propagation should be extremely fast. This increases efficiency and reduces the time it takes for transactions to be confirmed. Transaction creators benefit from weak blocks because they have a better understanding of whether or not their transactions are likely to be confirmed in the next block.Gavin Andresen proposed this new block propagation system, which incentivizes miners to create blocks with fee-paying transactions rather than empty blocks. If accepting the full-difficulty block and CreateNewBlock() operations can be made fast enough, miners will have an incentive to include fee-paying transactions in their blocks rather than mining empty ones. While there may be concerns about miners trying to avoid validation work, this disadvantage is outweighed by the benefits. By incentivizing miners to create blocks with fee-paying transactions rather than empty blocks, weak blocks could potentially increase revenue for miners. There is no significant increase in bandwidth or CPU usage associated with weak blocks since multiple weak blocks at a given point in time are likely to contain the same transactions.Various proposals have been made to optimize weak block protocols, including using forward-error-coded protocols (IBLTs) and caching Merkle nodes/subtrees. However, there are concerns about the potential issue of making mining not progress-free by using a scheme where a full solution must be exactly identical to a prior weak block. Instead, an optimized protocol that is forward-error-coded and does not require exact matching could be used. The implementation of this new block propagation system shouldn't increase bandwidth or CPU usage significantly.In addition, the conversation also explores the logic behind transitive relaying of announcements and the importance of relaying blocks to help the network. The proposed solution involves using forward-error-coded protocols (IBLTs) and merged mined block DAGs with blocks of arbitrary strength that are differentially coded against prior state to efficiently transmit new solutions regardless of who creates it and how different it is.However, there is a risk of making mining not progress-free because bigger miners would have more access to the weak/strong one/two punch. To avoid this, merged mined block DAGs with blocks of arbitrary strength were suggested. A hybrid system using a combination of IBLTs and Merkle tree encoding could also improve transmissibility.Overall, the proposal for weak blocks could work, but it requires careful consideration of the weak block commitment and its relationship with block commitment. Weak blocks add hashcash as a rate-limiting mechanism to solve the problem of miners trying to avoid validation work.</summary>
